Scala does something similarly neat with using #| for piping system commands.<p>Slash for Scala is not used by default though for path joining, but it can be by adding an implicit function:<p><pre><code>  implicit def slash(str: String) = new { def /(joinStr: String) = str + java.io.File.separatorChar + joinStr} 

  val joinedStr = &quot;abc&quot;/&quot;def&quot;/&quot;ghi&quot;
  > joinedStr : java.lang.String = abc/def/ghi
</code></pre>
Shell friendly syntax can be used for stdin/stdout in Scala as well (already in the stdlib with no implicits required):<p>#<   Redirect STDIN<p>#>   Redirect STDOUT<p>#>>  Append to STDOUT<p>#&&  Create an AND list<p>#!!  Create an OR list<p><a href=\http://stackoverflow.com/questions/12772605/scala-shell-commands-with-pipe/12772628" rel="nofollow">http://stackoverflow.com/questions/12772605/scala-shell-comm...</a><p><a href="http://alvinalexander.com/scala/scala-execute-exec-external-system-commands-in-scala" rel="nofollow">http://alvinalexander.com/scala/scala-execute-exec-external-...</a>"
